<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ881115-0126 </DOCNO><HL> Notable andamp; Quotable </HL><SO> </SO><TEXT>      Dorothy Conniff, head of the municipal day-care assistance program in Madison, Wis., writing on &quot;What's Best For the Child?&quot; in the November issue of The Progressive:   The value of &quot;motherhood&quot; has become a platitude, but it has so little moral force that, all over the country, we are forcing mothers to put their infants in day care so they can take jobs at the minimum wage. What does it say about our priorities that we feel it's more important for these women to flip hamburgers or clean hotel rooms than to care for their babies? </TEXT></DOC>